goals.question: What is the distribution of penguin species in the dataset?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of the count of each penguin species
goals.rationale: This helps us understand the proportion of each species in the dataset and if there is any class imbalance.

goals.question: What is the average body mass of each penguin species?
goals.visualization: Box plot of body mass for each penguin species
goals.rationale: This helps us compare the body mass of each species and identify any outliers or differences in distribution.

goals.question: What is the relationship between flipper length and body mass?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of flipper length vs body mass
goals.rationale: This helps us understand if there is a correlation between flipper length and body mass and if it varies by species.

goals.question: What is the distribution of bill length for each penguin species?
goals.visualization: Violin plot of bill length for each penguin species
goals.rationale: This helps us compare the distribution of bill length for each species and identify any differences or similarities.

goals.question: What is the gender distribution for each penguin species?
goals.visualization: Stacked bar chart of gender count for each penguin species
goals.rationale: This helps us understand if there is any gender bias in the dataset and if it varies by species.

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    sns.set(style="darkgrid")
    plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
    ax = sns.countplot(x="species", data=data, palette="Set2")
    ax.set(xlabel='Penguin Species', ylabel='Count')
    return plt

data = pd.read_json('penguins.json')
chart = plot(data)
```

```
import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Load data
data = pd.read_json('penguins.json')

# Create boxplot
sns.boxplot(x='species', y='body_mass_g', data=data)

# Set chart title
plt.title('What is the average body mass of each penguin species?', wrap=True)

# Add horizontal line for median body mass
medians = data.groupby(['species'])['body_mass_g'].median()
for i in range(len(medians)):
    plt.axhline(y=medians[i], color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Median: {medians[i]:.2f}g')

# Add legend
plt.legend()

# Show plot
plt.show()
```

```
# Add title and legend
plt.title('What is the relationship between flipper length and body mass?')
plt.legend(title='Species')

# Return plot
plt.show()
```
